In both Fig.~\ref{tempcompare} and Fig.~\ref{tempchi} , we depict the self-scattering cross section per SIMP mass, $\sigma_{\rm self}/m_\chi$, in dot-dashed lines, and impose the Planck $3\sigma$ values \cite{planck} on the relic density in light-blue region.  
As a result, the correct relic density can be obtained for the SIMP coupling of order one near the resonance, while the bounds on the self-scattering cross section, $\sigma_{\rm self}/m_\chi<1\,{\rm cm^2/g}$, obtained from Bullet cluster \cite{bullet} and halo shapes \cite{haloshape}, as well as unitartity and perturbativity bounds, are satisfied.  
The larger the width of the scalar field $S$, the larger the self-scattering cross section and the larger the parameter space satisfying the correct relic density and the bounds on self-scattering.  
We note that another resonance at $m_S=2m_\chi$ appears in both $2\rightarrow 2$ and $3\rightarrow 2$ processes, so the region near those additional resonances is disfavored by unitarity or bounds on self-scattering. 



Here, comments on the temperature effect near the resonance are in order. 
First, below the resonance with $\delta_S>0$,  the temperature effect decreases the $3\rightarrow 2$ annihilation cross section and the temperature integration of the Boltzmann equation is dominated by $x=m_\chi/T\sim v^{-2}_{\rm rel}\gtrsim 1/{\rm max}[\delta_S,\gamma_S]\gtrsim x_F$ where $x_F$ is given by $x_F\simeq 10-20$ at the freeze-out temperature without temperature effect. Thus, for $\delta_S\lesssim \gamma_S\lesssim x^{-1}_F$ or  $\gamma_S\lesssim \delta_S\lesssim x^{-1}_F$,  the effective freeze-out temperature is given by ${\tilde x}_F\sim 1/{\rm max}[\delta_S,\gamma_S]$, leading to the increase in the relic density, as $Y_\infty\sim {\tilde x}^4_F\gtrsim x^4_F$.  Therefore, in this case, in order to benefit from the resonance enhancement, we need to choose a relatively large width, such that the effective freeze-out temperature changes little.
On the other hand, for $ \gamma_S\lesssim x^{-1}_F\lesssim \delta_S$ or $\delta_S\lesssim x^{-1}_F\lesssim \gamma_S$ or $x^{-1}_F\lesssim \gamma_S, \delta_S$, the temperature effect becomes unimportant. 

Second, above the resonance with $\delta_S<0$, for $\delta_S\lesssim \gamma_S\lesssim x^{-1}_F$ or $\gamma_S\lesssim |\delta_S|\lesssim x^{-1}_F$, the temperature integration of the Boltzmann equation is dominated by the pole at $x=m_\chi/T\sim v^{-2}_{\rm rel}\sim 1/{\rm max}[\delta_S,\gamma_S]\gtrsim x_F$. In this case, the $3\rightarrow 2$ annihilation cross section is enhanced by a factor of ${\rm max}[\delta_S,\gamma_S]^2/{\rm min}[\delta_S,\gamma_S]^2$ as compared to the zero temperature case, while the effective freeze-out temperature is given by ${\tilde x}_F\sim 1/{\rm max}[\delta_S,\gamma_S]$.  In this case, the ratio of the relic density with temperature  effect to the one without temperature effect scales as $Y_\infty/ Y^0_\infty \sim ({\tilde x}^4_F/x^4_F){\rm max}[\delta_S,\gamma_S]^2/{\rm min}[\delta_S,\gamma_S]^2  \lesssim 1$, so the relic density is always reduced as compared to the case with zero temperature.  Therefore, in this case,  the resonance enhancement of the SIMP annihilation cross section works for any decay width of the field $S$ satisfying $|\delta_S|\lesssim x^{-1}_F$.   
On the other hand, for $\gamma_S\lesssim x^{-1}_F\lesssim |\delta_S|$ or $|\delta_S|\lesssim x^{-1}_F\lesssim \gamma_S$ or $x^{-1}_F\lesssim \gamma_S, \delta_S$, the temperature effect becomes unimportant. 








